import ChapterShell from "../../../components/ChapterShell.astro";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import DiagramFigure from "../../../components/diagrams/DiagramFigure.astro";
import CompactionProjectionKeystone from "../../../components/diagrams/CompactionProjectionKeystone.astro";
import CompactKindsFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/CompactKindsFlow.astro";
import HighWaterCompactFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/HighWaterCompactFlow.astro";
import RollingCheckpointFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/RollingCheckpointFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="03" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      Context windows fill; “remember everything” is a fantasy. Compaction lets the model lawfully
      forget older turns while historical facts remain recoverable from the log / evidence layer —
      what is forgotten is a projection, not the world. Key line:
      <strong>compaction is the Events Log's projection.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§03 · Scene"
    title="Start from a long-running session"
    lede="Full history still has value; the next call cannot and should not re-stuff thousands of facts into the prompt."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose the user and Maka work for two hours: reading a project, emitting huge test output,
      editing files, debating a wrong direction and rolling back, finishing a first fix, then asking
      for the next failing case. The full Runtime Events Log may hold thousands of facts — exact
      commands, tool results seen at the time, user constraints, a clue that becomes useful again
      later — all still true history.
    </p>
    <p>
      But the next model call usually needs only: current goal, done vs in-progress, irreversible
      decisions, current files and run state, next steps, and where to fetch originals when a summary
      is not enough. The most dangerous implementation conflates “need to keep working” with “need to
      keep truth”: generate a summary, then delete or overwrite the original events. If the model
      drops one constraint, the system has no stable source left to correct it.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      The question is not “how to make the chat shorter,” but: how do you compute a smaller
      continuation view for the next model decision while keeping the full event facts?
    </blockquote>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§03 · Keystone"
    title="Compaction is not mutation — it is projection"
    lede="Scene-local metaphor; fixed system is NewsLiquid tokens, hand keystones, and motion discipline."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · Canonical log → durable checkpoint → ephemeral provider request; source log remains replayable."
      alt="Runtime Events Log fans into HistoryCompactCheckpoint and recent raw Events tail; Materialize feeds a dashed Provider request; invariant: Compaction projects the log and never mutates canonical RuntimeEvents."
    >
      <CompactionProjectionKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p class="figure-note">
      In database terms, a checkpoint is closer to a materialized view than WAL truncation — it can be
      invalidated and rebuilt; it must not declare that the source log no longer matters.
    </p>

    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Projection relation">Canonical history = RuntimeEvents[0..n]

Compact checkpoint = Project(
  RuntimeEvents[0..k],
  compaction policy,
  summarizer
)

Next model context = Materialize(
  compact checkpoint,
  RuntimeEvents[k+1..n],
  provider capabilities,
  current context budget
)</pre>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="three-layers"
    label="§03 · Layers"
    title="Three non-interchangeable objects"
    lede="A summary is only text; a safe compaction projection must also bind coverage."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Runtime Events Log</strong> — semantic facts that user, model, tools, and Runtime
        already produced; the source of facts; details must not be lost to save context.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>History Compact Checkpoint</strong> — a continuation summary plus coverage for a
        verified event prefix; a durable projection, not a second truth.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Provider Request Messages</strong> — the working context this LLM call actually
        consumes; an ephemeral projection that may be recomputed under budget.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Ordinary “summaries” are only words. A safe checkpoint must also answer: which Session, how many
      ordered RuntimeEvents / Turns, where the prefix ends
      (<code>runId / turnId / runtimeEventId</code>), what the source digest is, whether it is a
      legal successor of the previous checkpoint, and whether it still fits the current token policy.
      A summary without coverage is a note; a summary without a digest cannot prove it still matches
      the current log.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Evolution aside</p>
      <p>
        LLM compaction architecture chapter land:
        <a href="/history/pr/772">maka:pr:772</a>
        (docs: add LLM compaction architecture chapter). Later V2 checkpoint / rolling / replay
        tightening:
        <a href="/history/pr/729">maka:pr:729</a>,
        <a href="/history/pr/955">maka:pr:955</a>,
        <a href="/history/pr/1090">maka:pr:1090</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="high-water"
    label="§03 · Trigger"
    title="High water decides whether to project"
    lede="Stable trigger semantics: cross the water → fold older prefix → keep raw tail → accept only if checkpoint+tail still fit."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · LLM produces summary value; Runtime owns coverage, durability, and replay gates."
      alt="Five-step flow: Past high water, LLM summary, Durable append, Coverage gate, Replay with raw tail."
    >
      <HighWaterCompactFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      Automatic history compaction is driven by <code>ContextBudgetPolicy</code>: compute a
      prior-history budget from the model context window; when compactable history crosses high water,
      fold. By default keep a bounded raw tail (newest complete Turns, never splitting a tool
      call/result pair). Token numbers are default policy, not protocol constants — what must stay
      stable is trigger and failure semantics.
    </p>
    <p>
      The LLM here generates a structured continuation summary meant for another LLM (Goal / Done /
      Key Decisions / Next Steps / Critical Context). Which events belong to the covered prefix, what
      the digest is, whether it may replace the current log, which raw tail to keep, and whether it is
      already durable — all decided by deterministic Runtime code.
      <strong>The LLM is the generator of the projection value, not the projection authority.</strong>
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="rolling"
    label="§03 · Rolling"
    title="Rolling checkpoint: do not re-summarize the whole world"
    lede="Long Sessions cross high water many times; re-compressing from zero is expensive and rewrites old facts."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · Rolling: feed only prior summary + newly folded into the summarizer; recompute full-prefix coverage."
      alt="Checkpoint N and Newly folded enter Summarizer, then Recompute cover yields Checkpoint N+1."
    >
      <RollingCheckpointFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Rolling checkpoint">Checkpoint N
  summary = S(events[0..k])

Newly evicted = events[k+1..m]

Checkpoint N+1
  summary = S(Checkpoint N.summary, newly evicted)
  coverage = events[0..m]
  previousCheckpointId = Checkpoint N.id</pre>
    <p>
      The summarizer receives only the previous summary and newly folded events; already-covered raw
      events are not re-fed to the LLM. The new checkpoint recomputes coverage and
      <code>sourceDigest</code> over the full covered prefix. The critical commit point is
      <code>history_compact_checkpoint_recorded</code> — a new summary may enter the same provider
      request as a replacement only after the durable recorder succeeds.
    </p>
    <p>
      Coverage must be an <strong>ordered prefix</strong>, not a search summary over an arbitrary
      event set. The prefix constraint makes replay <code>checkpoint + uncovered raw suffix</code>,
      keeps high water monotonically comparable, and makes newly folded events explicit. Prefix or
      digest failure → reject the checkpoint, never “looks like the same history.”
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="kinds"
    label="§03 · Boundaries"
    title="Do not merge three compacts into one feature"
    lede="They all shrink provider messages, but source, lifecycle, and durability strength differ."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · History LLM compaction (this chapter) ≠ Active prune (§02) ≠ semanticCompact (attention shaping)."
      alt="Three columns comparing History LLM compaction, Active Tool Result Prune, and semanticCompact."
    >
      <CompactKindsFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      Building on §02: active prune rewrites the provider-visible tool-result representation in the
      current Turn; raw is archived first; the evidence layer is not deleted. This chapter’s body is
      prior-history LLM compaction — when building prior history between Turns, a V2 checkpoint
      replaces an older event prefix. <code>semanticCompact</code> is mid-turn attention shaping with
      mostly best-effort recording; it is <strong>not</strong> the V2 history checkpoint protocol
      that only enters replay after a durable append succeeds.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="failure"
    label="§03 · Failure"
    title="Prefer seeing less over seeing a fake history"
    lede="Fail open to a safe source-derived context, not to an invented summary."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Empty LLM summary → do not record a new checkpoint; first compact keeps a safe raw tail only.</li>
      <li>
        Rolling summarizer fails → if the old checkpoint still matches and fits, reuse it and append
        the newest complete raw Turns that fit; <strong>never</strong> widen the old checkpoint’s
        coverage claim.
      </li>
      <li>
        Durable append fails → do not use the candidate; an uncommitted projection must not enter the
        model and then claim recoverability.
      </li>
      <li>
        Prefix / digest mismatch or over budget → reject replay; historically valid ≠ currently usable.
      </li>
      <li>
        Bounded projection corrupt → recover by scanning the canonical AgentRun ledger; cache is not
        the sole source of truth.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current · V2 preferred</p>
      <p>
        V2 ledger-backed <code>HistoryCompactCheckpoint</code> is the preferred main path; V1
        artifact-backed <code>HistoryCompactBlock</code> remains read-only compatible. Teaching
        centers the projection invariant; default token numbers are not protocol constants.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="not"
    label="§03 · Not"
    title="What Compaction is not"
    lede="Draw the line so a summary is not elevated into memory, deletion, or official conclusion."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Not Memory</strong> — serves current Session continuation, not a cross-Session knowledge base.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not deleting history</strong> — covered events leave this working set, not the canonical ledger.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not semantically lossless</strong> — digest proves which source span is covered, not that the
        summary has no omissions.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not bit-exact replay</strong> — rebuilds semantic origin; does not guarantee identical summary text.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not official conclusion</strong> — “tests passed” inside a summary is still a précis; authority
        stays with source / verifier / terminal fact (see §05).
      </li>
    </ul>
  </Section>

  <div slot="outline">
    <ul class="outline-list">
      <li>Present: keystone + high-water + rolling + three-compacts flows</li>
      <li>
        Aside: <a href="/history/pr/772">maka:pr:772</a>
      </li>
      <li>Still open: cold-start recovery figure, a11y pass — do not mark checklist complete</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</ChapterShell>

